### Changes made to the Google Form (Project 2 -> Project 4)

Rather than adding completely new questions, I initially decided to change the type of one of my existing questions instead. (Which now I regreted doing.)

After learning more types of visualisations and how to use the {lubridate} package, I realised I no longer needed my original question: 

“How many minutes has it been since the last meal?”

This question had originally been designed mainly for creating a simple bar graph using numeric values. I changed it into a question asking for the actual time of the previous meal instead, which transformed the response from a numeric variable into a time variable and gave me much more flexibility for analysing time patterns in R.

When importing the updated dataset into my R script, I first tried removing the older responses using:

`new_logged_data <- logged_data %>%`
`slice(30:nrow(logged_data))`

so that only the newer entries with the updated format would remain.
However, after I finished most of the project, I later tried opening my old Project 2 HTML file and realised it no longer worked properly, I assume it's because of the mixture of old and new data types which caused compatibility problems.

Since I wanted to preserve my original Project 2, I decided to duplicate my original Google Form.<br>
And to fix all problems, I:

* copied the original Google Form
* reverted the structure back to its original version
* manually re-entered the updated responses into the new form one by one, and copied in the old datas from project 2 and manually calculated and changed the numeric minutes of duration to the time I had last meal.
* removed new(inconsistent) data from the old dataset

This allowed Project 2 to function again as intended.

For Project 4, I imported the CSV connected to the new form instead. Since the timestamps in the copied form were no longer meaningful, I simply removed the Timestamp column and renamed the remaining variables:

`new_logged_data <- logged_data %>%`
`select(-Timestamp) %>%`
`rename(...)`

As the workflow was fairly dynamic, I only needed to change the imported CSV file and variable names — most of the rest of my code still worked without major changes.
