### Creating my data visualisations
I focus mainly on variables related to fullness duration, food type, portion size/fullness, and exercise — basically everything I collected — since the overall project is about understanding my eating habits and hunger patterns and I want the visualisations to show both behavioural patterns and relationships between variables.

For the hunger frequency graph, I chose a grouped bar chart because it clearly compared how often I felt hungry during different times of the day while also showing differences in portion size.

For the portion size and fullness duration graph, I used jittered points to display the raw observations and preserve variability in the data. I then added diamond-shaped summary points from a separate summarised dataset (exercise) to compare average behaviour between cases where I did or did not perform moderate exercise.

For the food type visualisation, I used boxplots with points so I could compare overall distributions while still showing individual observations. I also mapped fullness level to colour intensity to add another layer of information without needing a separate graph.
