## Visual data story

### [My visual data story webpage](https://ykmhk.github.io/stats220/visual_data_story.html)

My visual data story demonstrates creativity through both the design of my visualisations and the way I transformed the data.

For example, I used `mutate()` to create several new variables from the original form data rather than only analysing the raw responses directly. These included:
minutes_used_to_feel_hungry_again, created using `{lubridate}` and `difftime()` to calculate how 
* long it took before I felt hungry again
* did_moderate_exercise, created using `ifelse()` and detecting the word “moderate”
* meal_period, which grouped times into Morning, Afternoon, Evening, and Night to make temporal patterns easier to analyse

This allowed me to explore behavioural patterns that were not directly visible in the raw dataset.

I also demonstrated creativity by layering multiple variables into single visualisations instead of using only basic charts. 

For example, in my food type plot, I used `geom_jitter(aes(fill = fullness))` to map fullness levels to colour intensity, allowing the graph to communicate an additional variable without needing a separate plot.
In addition, I combined multiple geoms within the same graphs, such as:

* boxplots with jittered observations
* raw data with summarised mean points
* grouped bar charts with annotations

This layering approach helped make my visualisations both analytical and narrative-driven.
